The best approach for your file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already provides `IFileSystem` with mock support. No need to roll your own wrapper.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # in your test project
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs or Startup.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your class

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, $"Report: {reportName}");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

### Bonus — other statics in `ReportGenerator.cs`

I also noticed `DateTime.UtcNow`, `Environment.*`, and `Console.WriteLine` in that file. Since you're on .NET 10:

| Static | Recommended abstraction |
|---|---|
| `DateTime.UtcNow` | Inject `TimeProvider` (built-in). Register: `builder.Services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);` |
| `Environment.*` | Custom `IEnvironmentProvider` wrapping only `GetEnvironmentVariable` and `MachineName` |
| `Console.WriteLine` | Use `ILogger<T>` or a custom `IConsole` |

Want me to generate the `IEnvironmentProvider` wrapper or refactor `ReportGenerator.cs` with all the abstractions wired up?
